    <p>
        <m>\textbf{ Key Takeaway }</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        In the previous lesson, <xref ref="subsec-recurring-decimals"/>, we explored <alert>recurring decimals</alert>. 
        Now, we will learn how to convert recurring decimals into fractions. 
    </p>
    <p>
        To do this, we start by defining the decimal as an unknown variable, say <m>x</m>, and label this as equation <m>1</m>. 
        Next, we multiply both sides of equation <m>1</m> by <m>10^n</m>, where <m>n</m> represents the number of repeating digits, and label this as equation <m>2</m>. 
        Finally, we subtract equation <m>1</m> from equation <m>2</m> to eliminate the recurring part and solve for <m>x</m>. 
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Express each of the following as a fraction.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>0.\dot{2}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>0.\dot{6}\dot{3}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>0.\dot{2}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Step <m>1:</m> To convert the <m>0.\dot{2}</m> into a fraction, we let <m>0.\dot{2}</m> in the expanded form be equal to unkown variable, say, <m>x</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Now, <m> x = 0.2222...</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Step <m>2</m>: Identify the repeating digits.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            In this case we have only one repeating digit which is <m>2.</m>
                            We therefore multiply both sides of the equation in step <m>1</m> by <m>10^1 = 10.</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                10 x = 2.222...
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                           Step <m>3:</m> Subtract the result of step <m>1</m> from the result of step <m>2</m> to eliminate the recurring part.
                        </p>
                        <tabular>
                            <row>
                                <cell halign="right"><m>10x</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>2.2222...</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row bottom="medium">
                                <cell halign="right"><m>- x</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>0.2222...</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row bottom="medium">
                                <cell><m>9x</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                        <!-- <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> x \amp = 0.2222...</mrow>
                                <mrow> 10 x \amp = 2.2222...</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p> -->
                        <p>
                            Solve for <m>x</m>, by dividing both side of the equation by <m>9.</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\frac{\cancel{9}x}{\cancel{9}} \amp = \frac{2}{9} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp </mrow>
                                <mrow>x \amp = \frac{2}{9}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore, <m>0.\dot{2} = \frac{2}{9}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>0.\dot{6}\dot{3}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            We equate the recurring decimal to a variable, say <m>x</m>, to create equation <m>(1)</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <me>x  =  0.6363... \qquad \qquad \qquad \text{equation}(1)</me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Since <m>0.6363...</m> has two repeating digits, we multiply both sides of equation<m>(1)</m> by <m>100</m>
                            so that the recurring  digit of the decimals align (this creates equation <m>(2)</m>)
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <me>100x  =  63.63... \qquad \qquad \qquad \text{equation}(2)</me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Subtract equation<m>(1)</m> from equation<m>(2)</m>
                        </p>
                        <tabular>
                            <row>
                                <cell halign="right"><m>100x</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>63.63...</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row bottom="medium">
                                <cell halign="right"><m>- x</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>0.63...</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row bottom="medium">
                                <cell><m>99x</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>63</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                        <p>
                            Solve for <m>x</m>, by dividing both side of the equation by <m>99.</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>99x \amp= 63 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp </mrow>
                                <mrow>\frac{99x}{99} \amp= \frac{63}{99} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp= \frac{63}{99} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Simplify the fraction
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\frac{\cancel{63}^7}{\cancel{99}_{11}} = \frac{7}{11}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore, <m>0.\dot{6}\dot{3} = \frac{7}{11}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
